Reading in and writing data out in R

  1. Read CpG island (CpGi) data from the compGenomRData package CpGi.table.hg18.txt. This is a tab-separated file. Store it in a variable called cpgi.
cpgFilePath=system.file("extdata", "CpGi.table.hg18.txt", package="compGenomRData")
cpgi=read.table(cpgFilePath, header=TRUE, sep="\t")

  1. Write CpG islands to a text file called “my.cpgi.file.txt”. Write the file to your home folder.
write.table(cpgi, "my.cpgi.file.txt")
write.table(cpgi, "my.cpgi.file2.txt", quote=FALSE,sep="\t")
  1. Write out the first 10 rows of the cpgi data frame. HINT: Use subsetting for data frames we learned before.
write.table(cpgi[1:10,], "my.cpgi.file_10rows.txt", quote=FALSE,sep="\t")
  1. Write the first 3 columns of the cpgi data frame.
write.table(cpgi[,1:3], "my.cpgi.file_3cols.txt", quote=FALSE,sep="\t")
  1. Write CpG islands only on chr1. HINT: Use subsetting with [], feed a logical vector using == operator.
write.table(cpgi[cpgi$chrom == "chr1",], "my.cpgi.file_chr1.txt", quote=FALSE,sep="\t")

Plotting in R

Please run the following code snippet for the rest of the exercises.

set.seed(1001)
x1=1:100+rnorm(100,mean=0,sd=15)
y1=1:100
  1. Make a scatter plot using the x1 and y1 vectors generated above.
  2. Use the main argument to give a title to plot() as in plot(x,y,main=“title”).
  3. Use the xlab argument to set a label for the x-axis. Use ylab argument to set a label for the y-axis.
  4. Once you have the plot, run the following expression in R console. mtext(side=3,text=“hi there”) does.
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis")
mtext(side=3,text="hi there")

  1. See what mtext(side=2,text=“hi there”) does. Check your plot after execution.
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis")
mtext(side=2,text="hello there")

  1. Use mtext() and paste() to put a margin text on the plot. You can use paste() as ‘text’ argument in mtext(). HINT: mtext(side=3,text=paste(…)). See how paste() is used for below.
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis")
mtext(side=2,text=paste("General", "Kenobi"))

  1. cor() calculates the correlation between two vectors. Pearson correlation is a measure of the linear correlation (dependence) between two variables X and Y. Try using the cor() function on the x1 and y1 variables.
cor(x1,y1)
## [1] 0.855402
  1. Try to use mtext(),cor() and paste() to display the correlation coefficient on your scatter plot.
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis")
mtext(side=3,text=paste("Correlation:", cor(x1,y1)))

  1. Change the colors of your plot using the col argument. Ex: plot(x,y,col=“red”).
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis", col = "red")

  1. Use pch=19 as an argument in your plot() command.
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis", pch = 19)

  1. Use pch=18 as an argument to your plot() command.
plot(x1,y1, main = "Scatter plot", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Y axis", pch = 18)

  1. Make a histogram of x1 with the hist() function. A histogram is a graphical representation of the data distribution.
hist(x1)

  1. You can change colors with ‘col’, add labels with ‘xlab’, ‘ylab’, and add a ‘title’ with ‘main’ arguments. Try all these in a histogram.
hist(x1, main = "x1 histogram", col = "green3", xlab = "X axis", ylab = "Frequency")

  1. Make a boxplot of y1 with boxplot().
boxplot(y1)

  1. Make boxplots of x1 and y1 vectors in the same plot.
boxplot(x1, y1)

  1. In boxplot, use the horizontal = TRUE argument.
boxplot(x1, y1, horizontal = TRUE)

  1. Make multiple plots with par(mfrow=c(2,1)) • run par(mfrow=c(2,1)) • make a boxplot • make a histogram
par(mfrow=c(2,1))

# check if GC value is lower than 60,
# assign "low" to result

        result="low"
        cat("low")

  1. Write a function that takes a value of GC percent and decides if it is low, high, or medium: low < 60, high>75, medium is between 60 and 75. Fill in the values in the code below, where it is written ‘YOU_FILL_IN’.
GCclass<-function(my.gc){
if(my.gc < 60){
        result="low"
} else if(my.gc > 75) { # check if GC value is higher than 75,
        #assign "high" to result
        result="high"
} else{ # if those two conditions fail then it must be "medium"
        result="medium"
}
return(result)
}
GCclass(10) # should return "low"
## [1] "low"
GCclass(90) # should return "high"
## [1] "high"
GCclass(65) # should return "medium"
## [1] "medium"

  1. Is there a way to decide on the GC percentage class of a given vector of GCpercentages without using if/else structure and loops ? if so, how can you do it? HINT: Subsetting using < and > operators.
set.seed(42)
gcValues = data.frame(perCpg = rnorm(100, 65, 10))
gcValues$perCpg_class = "medium"

gcValues$perCpg_class[gcValues$perCpg > 75] = "high"
gcValues$perCpg_class[gcValues$perCpg < 60] = "low"

gcValues$perCpg_class = factor(gcValues$perCpg_class, levels = c("low", "medium", "high"))
